all_guidance.TableDefinition: Potentially Inappropriate Medication Use in Older Adults
all_guidance.Inclusion:
Avoid this rate control agent as FIRSTLINE therapy for atrial fibrillation or Afib
If used for atrial fibrillation or heart failure, avoid dosages >0.125 mg/day
all_guidance.Rationale:
Use in atrial fibrillation: should not be used as a first-line
agent in atrial fibrillation, because there are safer and
more effective alternatives for rate control supported by
high-quality evidence.
Use in heart failure: evidence for benefits and harms of
digoxin is conflicting and of lower quality; most but not all
of the evidence concerns use in HFrEF. There is strong
evidence for other agents as first-line therapy to reduce
hospitalizations and mortality in adults with HFrEF. In
heart failure, higher dosages are not associated with
additional benefit and may increase risk of toxicity.
Decreased renal clearance of digoxin may lead to
increased risk of toxic effects; further dose reduction may
be necessary in those with stage 4 or 5 chronic kidney
disease.
